    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Nov 12<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Huxley</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Many thanks for your Biology which I have read.— It was a real stroke of genius to think of such a plan.— Lord how I wish that I had gone through such a course.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Ever yours | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the reference to T. H. Huxley and Martin 1875 (see n. 2, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">A copy of <hi rend="italic">Course of practical instruction in elementary biology</hi> is in the Darwin Library–CUL (T. H. Huxley and Martin 1875). Each chapter of the book described a plant or animal organism, with a series of observations and experiments to be performed in a laboratory. The plan for the book arose out of Huxley’s teaching at the Royal School of Mines in South Kensington (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1979.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">A. Desmond 1994–7</ref>, 2: 35–9, 73).</note>
        </div>        
            
